ROB16697 | Introduction to Robotics Business | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=16697&SEMESTER=F16 | instructors:Bourne, David description:(For MRSD students only.) This course will help students develop business plans in the context of a new world filled with robots and robotic systems.  One of many examples is the new technology of driverless cars; every major automotive company has them in their product pipeline. What opportunities does this represent to a new robotics entrepreneur?  We help to identify an opportunity for a robotics business and explore the business fundamentals of how to build and manage it.  The first step is to develop an appropriate innovative idea that can find a profitable home in the marketplace.  To accomplish this, it is necessary to understand the prevalent trends of the current economic environment and how to market and position your product.  Here we utilize experts in marketing and innovation management.  The product may be a consumer product, or an improvement process  for some aspect of a business cycle (e.g., manufacturing or service).  However, we expect that the selected invention will be a new type of robot, a robotic application or part of an ever expanding robotic-ecosystem.  Please note that we have a very expansive view of what can count as a robot  Once a project area is selected we introduce the financial basics that are necessary to fund and sustain a new product initiative.  In the end, the product idea must be sold to either venture capitalists, private funding agents, corporate funding agents or government agencies.  The course is a project based and is executed by a team of you and your fellow students.  The final report can either be a business plan or a proposal for funding from an agency such as NSF (Small Business Innovation Research).  Professor Bourne has taught robotics to CMU business students since 1988.  Now for the first time he is teaching business to robotics students along with a handful of top CMU Tepper School Business Faculty.
ROB16698 | Advanced Topics in Robotics Business | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=16698&SEMESTER=S17 | instructors:Bourne, David description:This seminar course will expand some of the business themes from the previous Robotics Business course (16-697): human factors, marketing new business, financial planning for business, the art of negotiation, contracts and business ethics.  These technical topics will be interspersed with business cases to challenge students to analyze given business situations and to construct proposed solutions.  Material on US stock markets will also be presented to illustrate how public companies can be understood and tracked.  Senior professors from the Tepper School of Business, Lawyers and Corporate Executives will provide the lectures for the majority of the classes.  This year we will have special lectures from from a robotics company and a venture capitalist group  The project will build a business case for an existing public robotics company (or related technology company) and will FRAME a BUSINESS PROBLEM based on the live situation.  The students will then put together a detailed (written) case following the basic case structure outlined in 16-697,  Should Apple go into the driverless car business?  How will Tesla raise the money to build its car for the masses?  How can Fit compete with the Apple watch?  These are just a few possible projects in 2017.  Professor Bourne will moderate these classes.  David has taught robotics to CMU business students since 1988.  Now, he is teaching business to robotics students coordinated with experts in business.
